{"title_page": "Konami", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese entertainment and gaming company}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Konami Holdings Corporation\n| logo = Konami 4th logo 2.svg\n| image = Headquarters of KONAMI CORPORATION.JPG\n| image_size = 250px\n| image_caption = Konami's former headquarters complex in [[Tokyo Midtown]].\n| native_name = \u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u30db\u30fc\u30eb\u30c7\u30a3\u30f3\u30b0\u30b9\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\n| romanized_name = Konami H\u014drudingusu kabushiki gaisha\n| former_name = Konami Industry Co., Ltd. <small>(1973\u20131991)</small><br />Konami Co., Ltd <small>(1991\u20132000)</small><br />Konami Corporation <small>(2000\u20132015)</small>\n| type = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{Tokyo Stock Exchange|9766}}<br />{{LSE|KNM}}\n| ISIN = JP3300200007\n| industry = {{ubl|[[Video game industry|Video gaming]]|[[Entertainment]]}}\n| founded = {{start date and age|1969|3|21}}\n| founders = [[Kagemasa K\u014dzuki]]\n| location_city = [[Ginza]], [[Ch\u016b\u014d, Tokyo]]\n| location_country = [[Japan]]\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = Kagemasa Kozuki<br />{{small|(Chairman)}}<br />Takuya Kozuki<br />{{small|(President)}}<br>Kimihiko Higashio<br>{{small|(Vice President)}}\n| products = [[List of Konami games]]\n| revenue = {{increase}} [[Japanese yen|\u00a5]] 262.5 billion <small>([[Fiscal year#Japan|2019]])</small><ref name=\"konami.co.jp\">{{cite web|url=https://www.konami.com/ir/en/financialinfo/sales.html|title=Financial Highlights - KONAMI HOLDINGS CORPORATION|website=Konami.com|date=9 May 2019 |accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n| operating_income = {{increase}} [[Japanese yen|\u00a5]] 50.5 billion <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"konami.co.jp\"/>\n| net_income = {{increase}} [[Japanese yen|\u00a5]] 34.2 billion <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"konami.co.jp\"/>\n| num_employees = '''Konami (total)'''<br>10,454 (2019)<ref name=\"auto\"/><br>'''Konami Digital Entertainment'''<br>1,659<ref>https://www.konami.com/games/corporate/en/</ref><br>'''Konami Amusement'''<br>849<ref>https://www.konami.com/amusement/corporate/en/</ref><br>'''Konami Sports'''<br>6,249<ref>https://www.konami.com/sportsclub/corporate/</ref>\n| subsid = {{Unbulleted list\n| Konami Digital Entertainment\n| Konami Amusement\n| Konami Gaming\n| Konami Sports Club\n| Konami Sports Life\n| Konami Business Expert\n| Internet Revolution\n| KME\n| Konami Real Estate\n| [[Konami Cross Media NY]]\n| Kozuki Foundation\n}}\n| owner = Kozuki family (29%)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.konami.com/ir/en/stockbond/stockholderinfo/info/2016_0331.html?cm_sp=00-_-ir-_-stockbond-stockholderinfo-2016-0331-e|title=Shareholders Situation:As of March 31,2016 - KONAMI HOLDINGS CORPORATION|website=Konami.com|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref>\n| homepage = {{URL|www.konami.com}}\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo foot|'''Konami Holdings Corporation'''|\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u30db\u30fc\u30eb\u30c7\u30a3\u30f3\u30b0\u30b9|[[Kabushiki-gaisha]] Konami H\u014drudingusu|post=|group=nb|lead=yes}}<ref group=\"nb\">{{IPAc-en|IPA|k|o\u028a|\u02c8|n|\u0251\u02d0|m|i}} {{respell|koh|NAH|mee}}, {{IPA-ja|ko\ua71cnami|lang}}</ref> is a Japanese entertainment and gambling conglomerate. It operates as a [[product distributor]] (which produces and distributes [[trading card]]s, [[anime]], [[tokusatsu]], [[slot machine]]s, [[Pachinko|pachinko machines]] and [[List of Japanese arcade cabinets|arcade cabinets]]), [[video game developer]] and [[video game publisher|publisher]] company. Konami has casinos around the world and operates health and physical fitness clubs across Japan.\n\nKonami's video game franchisee include ''[[Metal Gear]]'', ''[[Silent Hill]]'', ''[[Castlevania]]'', ''[[Contra (series)|Contra]]'', ''[[Frogger]]'', ''[[Gradius]]'', ''[[Yu-Gi-Oh! Trading Card Game|Yu-Gi-Oh!]]'', ''[[Suikoden]]'' and ''[[Pro Evolution Soccer]]''. Additionally, Konami owns [[Bemani]], known for ''[[Dance Dance Revolution]]'' and ''[[Beatmania]]'', as well as the assets of former game developer [[Hudson Soft]], known for ''[[Bomberman]]'', ''[[Adventure Island (video game)|Adventure Island]]'', ''[[Bonk (series)|Bonk]]'', ''[[Bloody Roar]]'' and ''[[Star Soldier]]''. Konami is the twentieth-largest [[List of video game companies|game company]] in the world by revenue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newzoo.com/free/rankings/top-25-companies-by-game-revenues/|year=2015|title=Top 25 gaming companies|website=Newzoo.com|author=|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe company originated in 1969 as a [[jukebox]] rental and repair business in [[Toyonaka, Osaka]], [[Japan]], by [[Kagemasa K\u014dzuki]], who remains the company's chairman. The name ''Konami'' is a portmanteau of the names Kagemasa '''Ko'''zuki, Yoshinobu '''Na'''kama, and Tatsuo '''Mi'''yasako.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hongkiat.com/blog/popular-gaming-companies-names/|year=2013|title=The Stories Behind the Names of 15 Gaming Brands You Know|website=Hongkiat.com|author=Kelvon Yeezy|accessdate=21 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nKonami is headquartered in [[Tokyo]]. In the United States, Konami manages its video game business from offices in [[El Segundo, California]] and its casino gaming business from offices in [[Paradise, Nevada]]. Its Australian gaming operations are located in [[Sydney]]. As of March 2019, it owns 22 consolidated subsidiaries around the world.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.konami.com/corporate/en/data/|title=Corporate Data - KONAMI HOLDINGS CORPORATION|website=Konami.com|date=31 March 2019|accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:MCM London 2014 - Yu-Gi-Oh! (14269394494).jpg|thumb|The [[Yu-Gi-Oh! Trading Card Game]] is developed and published by Konami. In 2011, [[Guinness World Records]] called it the top-selling trading card game in history, with {{formatnum:25.2 billion}} cards sold worldwide.<ref name=\"Guinness\">{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-7000/best-selling-trading-card-game/|title=Best-selling trading card game company - cumulative|publisher=[[Guinness World Records]]|date=March 31, 2011|accessdate=March 5, 2014}}</ref>]]\n\nThe company was founded on March 21, 1969, and was officially incorporated under the name {{nihongo4|Konami Industry Co., Ltd.|\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u5de5\u696d\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e|Konami K\u014dgy\u014d Kabushiki Gaisha}} on March 19, 1973.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.konami.com/corporate/en/data/|title=Corporate Data - KONAMI HOLDINGS CORPORATION|last=KONAMI|website=Konami.com|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=IGN-history>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/companies/konami|title=Konami History|publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=6 August 2015}}</ref> The company's founder and chairman, Kagemasa Kozuki, ran a jukebox rental and repair business in [[Toyonaka, Osaka]] before transforming the business into a manufacturer of amusement machines for video arcades. Their first coin-operated video game was released in 1978, and they began exporting products to the United States the following year.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web|url=https://www.konami.com/corporate/en/history/|title=Corporate History - KONAMI HOLDINGS CORPORATION|last=KONAMI|date=|website=www.konami.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arcade-museum.com/manuf_detail.php?manuf_id=1467&orig_game_id=&sort=3|title=Konami - coin-operated machines|author=|date=|website=www.arcade-museum.com}}</ref>\n\nKonami began to achieve success with hit arcade games such as 1981's ''[[Frogger]]'', ''[[Scramble (video game)|Scramble]]'', and ''[[Super Cobra]]'', many of which were licensed to other companies for stateside release, including [[Stern (game company)|Stern Electronics]] and [[Gremlin Industries]].  They eventually established their U.S. subsidiary, Konami of America, Inc. in 1982. It was during this period that Konami began expanding their video game business into the home consumer market following a brief stint releasing video games for the [[Atari 2600]] in 1982 for the U.S. market.<ref name=konami_2600>{{cite web|url=http://www.video-game-ephemera.com/012.htm|title=Article 12\u2014KONAMI CES BROCHURE (1983) |website=VIDEO-GAME-EPHEMERA.com}}</ref> The company would release numerous games for the [[MSX]] home computer standard in 1983, followed by the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] in 1985.<ref name=konami_msx_catalog_1>{{cite web|title=MSX software catalog (1983\u20131986)|website=Konami Group Homepage|language=Japanese|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/cs/msx.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19961108212537/http://www.konami.co.jp/cs/msx.html|archive-date=1996-11-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=MSX software catalog (1987\u20131990)|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/cs/msx2.html|website=Konami Group Homepage|language=Japanese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19961108212544/http://www.konami.co.jp/cs/msx2.html|archive-date=1996-11-08}}</ref> Numerous Konami franchises were established during this period on both platforms, as well as the arcades, such as ''[[Gradius]]'', ''[[Castlevania]]'', ''[[Twin Bee]]'', ''[[Ganbare Goemon]]'', ''[[Contra (video game series)|Contra]]'' and ''[[Metal Gear]]''. Due to the success of their NES games, Konami's earnings grew from $10 million in 1987 to $300 million in 1991.<ref>{{cite journal|last= |first= |title=75 Power Players|journal=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=11|publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=November 1995|page=69}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1991, Konami's legal name was changed to {{nihongo4|Konami Co., Ltd.|\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e|Konami Kabushiki Gaisha}} and their headquarters would later be relocated to [[Minato, Tokyo]] in April 1993.<ref name=\"History\"/> The company started supporting the 16-bit video game consoles during this period, starting with the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]] in 1990, followed by the [[TurboGrafx-16|PC Engine]] in 1991 and the [[Sega Genesis]] in 1992.\n\nAfter the launch of the [[Sega Saturn]] and [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] in 1994, Konami became a business divisional organization with the formation of various Konami Computer Entertainment (KCE) subsidiaries, starting with KCE Tokyo and KCE Osaka (which would be later known as KCE Studios) in April 1995, followed by KCE Japan (later known as [[Kojima Productions]]) in April 1996. Each KCE subsidiary would end up creating different [[intellectual properties]] such as KCE Tokyo's ''[[Silent Hill]]'' series and KCE Japan's ''[[Metal Gear Solid]]'' series (a revival of the ''[[Metal Gear]]'' series on [[MSX]]). In 1997, Konami started producing [[rhythm game]]s for arcades under the [[Bemani]] brand and branched off into the [[collectible card game]] business with the launch of the [[Yu-Gi-Oh! Trading Card Game]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/9/28/17910944/dance-dance-revolution-anniversary|title=Dance Dance Revolution made watching games fun before Twitch|author=|date=|website=polygon.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thegamer.com/yu-gi-oh-cards-rare/|title=The 25 Rarest Yu-Gi-Oh Cards (And What They're Worth)|author=|date=18 August 2018|website=thegamer.com}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2000, the company's legal English name was changed to Konami Corporation, but the Japanese legal name remained the same. As the company transitioned into the developing video games for the sixth-generation consoles, they branched out into the health and fitness business with the acquisitions of People Co., Ltd and Daiei Olympic Sports Club, Inc., which became  Konami subsidiaries. In August 2001, Konami invested in another video game developer, [[Hudson Soft]], which became a consolidated subsidiary after Konami accepted new third-party shares issued by them. In March 2006, Konami merged all their video game development divisions into a new subsidiary known as Konami Digital Entertainment Co. (KDE), as the parent company became a pure holding company. Their headquarters were relocated to Minato, Tokyo, in 2007.<ref name=\"History\"/>\n\nThe absorption of [[Hudson Soft]] in 2012 resulted in the addition of several other franchises including: ''[[Adventure Island (video game)|Adventure Island]]'', ''[[Bonk (series)|Bonk]]'', ''[[Bloody Roar]]'', ''[[Bomberman]]'', ''[[Far East of Eden]]'' and ''[[Star Soldier]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/04/nintendo-should-buy-these-5-hudson-soft-games-from.html|title=5 Hudson Soft Games Nintendo Should Buy From Konami|author=|date=|website=pastemagazine.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.konami.com/games/jp/ja/products/search/?page=1&cat=gs&platform=Wii|title=\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u4e00\u89a7 - \u5bb6\u5ead\u7528\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0 - Wii - KONAMI \u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u88fd\u54c1\u30fb\u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9\u60c5\u5831\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8|author=|date=|website=KONAMI \u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u88fd\u54c1\u30fb\u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9\u60c5\u5831\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Konami delisted itself from the New York Stock Exchange following the dissolution of their Kojima Productions subsidiary.<ref name=\"delisting\">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/4/27/8503893/konami-delists-itself-from-new-york-stock-exchange|title=Konami delists itself from New York Stock Exchange|author=Brian Crecente|work=Polygon}}</ref>  In a translated interview with Nikkei Trendy Net published in the following month, the newly appointed CEO of Konami Digital Entertainment, Hideki Hayakawa, announced that Konami would shift their focus towards mobile gaming for a while, claiming that \"mobile is where the future of gaming lies.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/5/14/8605313/konami-interview-mobile-is-where-the-future-of-gaming-lies|title=Konami CEO: 'Mobile is where the future of gaming lies'|last=Crecente|first=Brian|date=2015-05-14|website=Polygon|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-07}}</ref> The trade name of the company was changed from Konami Corporation to Konami Holdings Corporation during the same month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/en/corporate/history/|title=Corporate History|publisher=Konami|accessdate=2015-11-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Konami announced that they would be reviving some of the company's other well-known video game titles following the success of their [[Nintendo Switch]] launch title ''[[Super Bomberman R]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Zarra|first1=Jonathan|title=Super Bomberman R Sales Indicate That It's The Best Selling In Its Franchise In Nearly 20 Years|url=http://nintendork.org/nintendo/super-bomberman-r-sales-indicate-that-its-the-best-selling-in-its-franchise-in-nearly-20-years/|website=Nintendork|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2020, Konami moved their headquarters to the [[Ginza]] district of Tokyo, which includes a facility for holding [[esports]] events as well as a school for esports players.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Batchelor |first1=James |title=Mobile, PES and esports: The three pillars of Konami |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-09-02-mobile-pes-and-esports-the-three-pillars-of-konami |website=GamesIndustry.biz |accessdate=19 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Corporate structure==\n\n===Japan===\n[[File: Konami booth, Taipei Game Show 20170123a.jpg|thumb|Konami Digital Entertainment booth at Taipei Game Show 2017]]\n[[File:KONAMI SPORTS CLUB Toyohashi.jpg|thumb|Konami Sports Club in [[Toyohashi]]. Konami Sports & Life operates fitness clubs across Japan.]]\n* Konami Holdings Corporation\n* Konami Digital Entertainment Co., Ltd.\n* Konami Sports & Life Co., Ltd.\n* Konami Amusement Co., Ltd.\n* Konami Real Estate, Inc.\n* KPE, Inc.\n* Konami Manufacturing and Service, Inc.\n* Konami Facility Service, Inc.\n* KME Co., Ltd.\n* Takasago Electric Industry Co., Ltd.\n* [[Hudson Soft|Hudson Soft Company, Limited]]: On January 20, 2011, Konami Corporation announced turning Hudson Soft Co., Ltd. as its wholly subsidiary via share exchange. The exchange became effective on April 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/1101/release2_english.pdf|title=KONAMI CORPORATION Announces that It will Make a Subsidiary (HUDSON SOFT CO., LTD.) Its Wholly Owned Subsidiary through Share Exchange|access-date=5 November 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6E80cTXte?url=http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/1101/release2_english.pdf|archive-date=2 February 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Digital Golf, Inc.: On January 20, 2011, Konami Corporation announced the acquisition of Digital Golf via share exchange. Digital Golf would become a wholly owned subsidiary of Konami. The exchange became effective on March 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/1101/release_english.pdf|title=KONAMI CORPORATION Announces that It will Make DIGITAL GOLF Inc. Its Wholly Owned Subsidiary through Share Exchange|access-date=5 November 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6E80d4fpT?url=http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/1101/release_english.pdf|archive-date=2 February 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Internet Revolution, Inc.\n* Biz Share Corporation\n* Combi Wellness Corporation\n* The Club At Yebisu Garden Co., Ltd.\n* Konami Holdings Corporation<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/2015/0508/ja_8r5gxy.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-09-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150818102853/http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/2015/0508/ja_8r5gxy.pdf |archivedate=2015-08-18 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inside-games.jp/article/2015/05/09/87448.html|title=\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u300110\u67081\u65e5\u4ed8\u3051\u3067\u300c\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u30db\u30fc\u30eb\u30c7\u30a3\u30f3\u30b0\u30b9\u300d\u306b\u5546\u53f7\u3092\u5909\u66f4 - \u30a4\u30f3\u30b5\u30a4\u30c9|website=Konami.co.jp|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Australia===\n* Konami Australia Pty Ltd (established in 1996)\n\n===America===\n[[File:Konami America booth, E3 20060511.jpg|thumb|Konami America booth at [[E3 2006]]]]\n\n* Konami Corporation of America: Current U.S.-based [[holding company]].\n* Konami Digital Entertainment, Inc.: former American holding company, formerly Konami of America Inc., Konami Corporation of America. On October 13, 2003, Konami Corporation of [[Redwood City, California]] announced it was expanding its operations to El Segundo, California, under the new name of Konami Digital Entertainment, Inc. The Redwood City operations have since been consolidated to El Segundo in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.com/gs/press/konami101303.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060929075753/http://www.konami.com/gs/press/konami101303.html|archivedate=2006-09-29|title=KONAMI ESTABLISHES NEW COMPUTER & VIDEO GAMES OPERATION BASED IN LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA}}</ref>\n** Konami Gaming, Inc. in [[Paradise, Nevada]].\n**[[Konami Cross Media NY]]\n\n===Europe===\n* Konami Digital Entertainment B.V.: European-based holding company.\n* Konami Digital Entertainment GmbH: former holding company Europe, formerly Konami Limited, Konami Corporation of Europe B.V. On March 31, 2003, Konami of Europe announced it would be renamed as Konami Digital Entertainment GmbH at the start of Konami's new financial year, on April 1, 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami-digital-entertainment.de/news.do;jsessionid=335BA44513A82C9A7A42105616EF98EC?idNews=6|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080529143817/http://www.konami-digital-entertainment.de/news.do?idNews=6|archivedate=2008-05-29|title=Introducing Konami Digital Entertainment GmbH}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\n* Konami Digital Entertainment Limited (\u79d1\u6a02\u7f8e\u6578\u78bc\u5a1b\u6a02\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8): Established in September 1994 as Konami (Hong Kong) Limited. Korea and Singapore divisions were established in October 2000. In June 2001, the company changed name to Konami Marketing (Asia) Ltd. (\u79d1\u6a02\u7f8e\u884c\u92b7(\u4e9e\u6d32)\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8). In March 2006, the company was renamed Konami Digital Entertainment Limited.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami-digital-entertainment.hk/aboutus.php?lang=en|title=About Us (English)|website=Konami-digital-entertainment.hk|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami-digital-entertainment.hk/aboutus.php?lang=cn-t|title=About Us (Chinese)|website=Konami-digital-entertainment.hk|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref>\n* Konami Software Shanghai, Inc. (\u79d1\u4e50\u7f8e\u8f6f\u4ef6\uff08\u4e0a\u6d77\uff09\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8): Established in June 2000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.konamish.com.cn/aboutus.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-11-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027224243/http://www.konamish.com.cn/aboutus.html |archivedate=2011-10-27 }}</ref>\n* Konami Digital Entertainment Co. (\uc8fc\uc2dd\ud68c\uc0ac \ucf54\ub098\ubbf8 \ub514\uc9c0\ud138 \uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8): [[South Korea]]-based game producer and distributor, originally established as the Korea branch of Konami Digital Entertainment Limited. On May 1, 2008, it became a separate company, and inherited the existing operations of the former Korea branch in June 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami-korea.kr/company_intro.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080628165903/http://www.konami-korea.kr/company_intro.html|archivedate=2008-06-28|title=KONAMI DIGITAL ENTERTAINMENT \ud68c\uc0ac \uc18c\uac1c}}</ref>\n\nOn November 7, 2005, Konami Corporation announced restructuring Konami Corporation into a holding company, by moving its Japanese Digital Entertainment Business segment under Konami Corporation. The Digital Entertainment Business would become Konami Digital Entertainment Co., Ltd. The newly established Konami Corporation was expected to begin operation on March 31, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2005/11/041/r.17.11.07-e.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110104061140/http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2005/11/041/r.17.11.07-e.html|archivedate=2011-01-04|title=Announcement of Group Restructuring (Merger Between Subsidiaries, Stock Exchange with subsidiary) and Shift to Holding Company Structure by Company Separation}}</ref>\n\n===Konami Digital Entertainment===\n[[File:PASELI Charger.JPG|thumb|[[Paseli]] Charger. Paseli (\u30d1\u30bb\u30ea) is an Electronic Money launched in 2010 by Konami Amusement.]]\n{{nihongo|Konami Digital Entertainment Co., Ltd.|\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u30c7\u30b8\u30bf\u30eb\u30a8\u30f3\u30bf\u30c6\u30a4\u30f3\u30e1\u30f3\u30c8|Kabushiki-gaisha Konami Dejitaru Entateinmento}} is Konami's Japanese video game development and publishing division founded on March 31, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.konami.com/games/corporate/ja/|title=\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u30c7\u30b8\u30bf\u30eb\u30a8\u30f3\u30bf\u30c6\u30a4\u30f3\u30e1\u30f3\u30c8 - \u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u30c7\u30b8\u30bf\u30eb\u30a8\u30f3\u30bf\u30c6\u30a4\u30f3\u30e1\u30f3\u30c8|website=Konami.com|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> Before Konami Corporation had formally changed to a holding company in 2006, various forms of Konami Digital Entertainment companies had been established either as holding company or publisher. The last of the company, the Japan-based Konami Digital Entertainment Co., Ltd., was split from Konami Corporation during the holding company restructuring process.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\n====Subsidiaries====\n*Konami Digital Entertainment Co., Ltd.: Japanese division, established on March 31, 2003.\n*Konami Digital Entertainment, Inc.: North American division, established on October 13, 2003.\n*Konami Digital Entertainment GmbH: European division, established on April 1, 2003.\n*Konami Digital Entertainment Limited: Hong Kong division. Established in September 1994 as Konami (Hong Kong) Limited. In March 2006, it was renamed to Konami Digital Entertainment Limited.\n*KME Co., Ltd (KME Corporation): music division established on October 1, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami-digital-entertainment.co.jp/kme/|title=KME\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e|date=29 May 2011|accessdate=9 November 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110529093217/http://www.konami-digital-entertainment.co.jp/kme/|archivedate=29 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Former subsidiaries===\nKonami Computer Entertainment Nagoya, Inc. (KCEN), founded on October 1, 1996,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/kcen/index.html |title=Company Info |work=\uff2b\uff23\uff25\u540d\u53e4\u5c4b\u30db\u30fc\u30e0\u30da\u30fc\u30b8 |publisher=Konami Co., Ltd. |accessdate=21 August 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021203213358/http://www.konami.co.jp/kcen/index.html |archivedate=3 December 2002}}</ref> was dissolved along with Konami Computer Entertainment Kobe, Inc. (KCEK) in December 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/0212/e/english.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110104174218/http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/0212/e/english.pdf|archivedate=2011-01-04 |title=Consolidated Financial Results for the Third Quarter and the Nine Months Ended December 31, 2002 |date=13 February 2003 |work=Investor Relations |publisher=Konami Co., Ltd. |accessdate=21 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2004, Konami Corporation announced Konami Online, Inc., Konami Computer Entertainment Studios, Inc., Konami Computer Entertainment Tokyo, Inc., Konami Computer Entertainment Japan, Inc. would merge into Konami Corporation, effective on March 1, 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2004/12/045/r.16.12.16-e.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110104083553/http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2004/12/045/r.16.12.16-e.html|archivedate=2011-01-04|title=Konami's Merger with Konami Online}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2004/12/044/r.16.12.16-e.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110104081854/http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2004/12/044/r.16.12.16-e.html|archivedate=2011-01-04|title=Konami's Merger with its Subsidiaries}}</ref>\n\nOn February 22, 2005, Konami Corporation announced Konami Media Entertainment, Inc. would merge into Konami Corporation, effective on March 1, 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2005/02/002/r.17.02.22-e.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110104053544/http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2005/02/002/r.17.02.22-e.html|archivedate=2011-01-04|title=Konami \u2013 KME Merger Announcement}}</ref>\nOn March 11, 2005, Konami Corporation announced Konami Traumer, Inc would be merged back into Konami Corporation, effective on June 1, 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2005/04/013/r.17.04.11-e.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110104045920/http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2005/04/013/r.17.04.11-e.html|archivedate=2011-01-04|title=Announcement: Merger of Konami and Konami Traumer}}</ref>\n\nOn January 5, 2006, Konami Corporation announced the merger of Konami Sports Corporation merged with its parent company, Konami Sports Life Corporation. The parent would be dissolved under the merger, and Konami Sports would become the wholly owned subsidiary of Konami Corporation after share exchange between KC and KS. After the share exchange, KS would be renamed Konami Sports & Life Co., Ltd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2006/01/001/r.18.01.05-e.html|title=Announcement of official agreement for group restructuring (merger between subsidiaries, share exchange with subsidiary) and shift to holding company structure by company separation|website=Konami.co.jp|accessdate=9 November 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090609031519/http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2006/01/001/r.18.01.05-e.html|archivedate=9 June 2009}}</ref> On February 28, 2006, Konami Sports Corporation merged with its parent company, Konami Sports Life Corporation, and became Konami Sports Corporation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konamisportsandlife.com/history/index.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422191741/http://www.konamisportsandlife.com/history/index.html|archivedate=2008-04-22|title=Konami Sports & Life history}}</ref>\n\nOn September 21, 2010, Konami Corporation announced it has signed an agreement to acquire with Abilit Corporation via share exchange. After the transaction, Abilit Corporation became a wholly owned subsidiary of Konami Corporation, effective January 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/9766.T/key-developments/article/1982065|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120910084554/http://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/9766.T/key-developments/article/1982065|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-09-10|title=KONAMI CORPORATION to Acquire Abilit Corporation through Stock Swap | work=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/1009/1009_release_english.pdf|title=Execution of Share Exchange Agreement by and between KONAMI CORPORATION and ABILITY CORPORATION|website=Konami.co.jp|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> On January 1, 2011, Abilit Corporation was renamed to Takasago Electric Industry Co.,Ltd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=2445690|title=Abilit Corp.: Private Company Information|website=Investing.businessweek.com|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> As part of the acquisition, Biz Share Corporation also became a subsidiary of Konami Corporation.\n\n====Megacyber Corporation====\nOn October 2, 2006, Konami Corporation announced it had completed the acquisition of mobile phone content developer Megacyber Corporation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/en/news/topics/061002/index.html|title=Announcement of Share Acquisition of Megacyber Corporation|website=Konami.co.jp|accessdate=9 November 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221194718/http://www.konami.co.jp/en/news/topics/061002/index.html|archivedate=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn February 6, 2007, Konami Corporation announced Megacyber Corporation to be merged into Konami Digital Entertainment Co., Ltd., with Konami Digital Entertainment Co., Ltd. being the surviving company, effective on April 1, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/en/news/topics/070206/|title=Announcement of Merger of Konami Digital Entertainment Co., Ltd. and Megacyber Corporation|website=Konami.co.jp|accessdate=9 November 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707180751/http://www.konami.co.jp/en/news/topics/070206/|archivedate=7 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Video games==\n{{main | List of Konami games}}\n[[File:DDR X2.png|thumb|[[Dance Dance Revolution X2]] machine created by Konami.]]\nMajor titles by Konami include the action ''[[Castlevania]]'' series, the survival horror ''[[Silent Hill]]'' series, the action shooter ''[[Contra (video game series)|Contra]]'' series, the platform adventure ''[[Legend of the Mystical Ninja (series)|Ganbare Goemon]]'' series, the stealth action ''[[Metal Gear]]'' series, the role-playing ''[[Suikoden]]'' series, the ''[[List of Bemani series|Bemani]]'' rhythm game series (which includes ''[[Dance Dance Revolution]]'', ''[[Beatmania IIDX]]'', ''[[GuitarFreaks]]'', ''[[DrumMania]]'', and ''[[Pop'n Music]]'', among others), ''[[Dancing with the Stars (video game)|Dancing with the Stars]]'', the dating simulation ''[[Tokimeki Memorial]]'' series, and football simulation ''[[Pro Evolution Soccer]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=A league of their own: six of the best football video games |url=https://www.theguardian.com/games/2018/aug/28/six-best-football-video-games-fifa-pro-evolution-soccer |accessdate=3 November 2018 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nKonami produced its [[shoot 'em up]] arcade games such as ''[[Gradius]]'', ''[[Salamander (video game)|Life Force]]'', ''[[Time Pilot]]'', ''[[Gyruss]]'', ''[[Parodius (series)|Parodius]]'', ''[[Axelay]]'', and ''[[TwinBee]]''. Konami's games based on cartoon licenses, especially the ''[[Batman: The Animated Series]]'', ''[[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles]]'', ''[[Tiny Toon Adventures]]'' and ''[[Animaniacs]]'' series, but other American productions like ''[[The Simpsons]]'', ''[[Bucky O'Hare]]'', ''[[G.I. Joe]]'', ''[[X-Men]]'' and ''[[The Goonies]]'' and French comic ''[[Asterix]]'' all have seen release at some point in the past by Konami either on arcades and/or video game consoles.\n\nSome cinematically styled franchises from Konami are ''[[Silent Hill]]'' [[survival horror]] franchise, and the ''Metal Gear'' series. Another successful franchise is ''[[Pro Evolution Soccer (series)|Winning Eleven]]'', the spiritual sequel to ''[[International Superstar Soccer]]''. In Japan, it is known for the popular ''Jikky\u014d Powerful Pro Yaky\u016b series'' baseball series and the ''[[Zone of the Enders]]'' games. The company has picked up ''[[Saw (video game)|Saw]]'' from [[Brash Entertainment]] when the game's production had been suspended due to financial issues.<ref name=Bloody-Disgusting3>{{cite web|date=2009-02-05|url=http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/12266/|title=Saw videogame picked up by Konami?|accessdate=2009-02-06}}</ref>\n\nKonami is known for its password, the [[Konami Code]], which traditionally gives many [[power-up]]s in its games.\n\n==Film production==\nIn 2006, Konami started producing films based on their franchises. Konami produced the [[Silent Hill (film)|''Silent Hill'' film]] (released in 2006) and announced that they will produce a [[Metal Gear Solid (film)|''Metal Gear Solid'' film]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://videogames.yahoo.com/newsarticle?eid=456314&page=0|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313014619/http://videogames.yahoo.com/newsarticle?eid=456314&page=0|archivedate=2007-03-13|title=Where did the Video Games site go?|publisher=Yahoo}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism and controversy==\n===''Silent Hills'' and reduced video game development===\n{{see also|Silent Hills|P.T. (video game)#Legacy}}\n\n''Silent Hills'', set to be the ninth installment of the ''Silent Hill'' franchise, was abruptly cancelled on April 2015 without explanation despite the critical acclaim and success of ''[[P.T. (video game)|P.T.]]'', a playable teaser.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Dave|title=What it's like to play the best game of 2014, which is about to disappear forever in 2 days|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/silent-hills-pt-review-2015-4|website=Business Insider|accessdate=24 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Orland|first1=Kyle|title=Discontinued PS4 horror demo P.T. worth hundreds on eBay|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2015/05/discontinued-ps4-horror-demo-p-t-worth-hundreds-on-ebay/|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=24 December 2015}}</ref> Hours after the announcement, Konami delisted itself from the New York Stock Exchange.<ref name=\"delisting\" />\n\nGame co-director and writer [[Guillermo del Toro]] publicly criticized the cancellation as not making any sense and questioned what he described as a \"scorched earth\" approach to removing the trailer. Due to the experience, del Toro stated that he would never work on another video game.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Parfitt|first1=Ben|title=Del Toro says killing Silent Hills 'makes no f***ing sense'|url=https://www.mcvuk.com/business/del-toro-says-killing-silent-hills-makes-no-fing-sense|website=MCV|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref><ref>Kuchera, Ben. [https://www.polygon.com/2016/12/2/13817080/guillermo-del-toro-fuck-konami-death-stranding Guillermo del Toro has a simple message: \u2018Fuck Konami\u2019]. [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]. Retrieved on May 10, 2018.</ref>\n\nKonami's CEO, Hideki Hayakawa, announced that \u2013 with few exceptions \u2013 Konami would stop making console games and instead focus on the [[mobile gaming]] platform, a decision that was heavily criticized by the video gaming community.<ref>Crecente, Brian. [https://www.polygon.com/2015/5/14/8605313/konami-interview-mobile-is-where-the-future-of-gaming-lies Konami CEO: 'Mobile is where the future of gaming lies']. [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]. Retrieved on February 11, 2018. Hideki Hayakawa: \"Gaming has spread to many platforms, but at the end of the day, the platform that is always closest to us, is mobile. Mobile is where the future of gaming lies...with multiplatform games, there's no point in dividing the market into categories anymore. Mobiles will take on the new role of linking the general public to the gaming world.\u201d([http://jin115.com/archives/52080348.html Original interview in Japanese])</ref><ref>Usher, William. [https://www.cinemablend.com/games/Konami-Stop-Making-Console-Games-Report-Says-86487.html Konami Will Stop Making Console Games, Report Says]. Cinemablend. Retrieved on January 29, 2018</ref><ref>Knapp, Mark. [https://gamerant.com/konami-gaming-financial-outlook/ Konami Shares Financial Outlook for Gaming]. Gamerant. retrieved on January 29, 2018</ref><ref>McFerran, Damien. [http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/04/konamis_creating_a_new_castlevania_but_its_not_coming_to_consoles Konami's Creating A New Castlevania, But It's Not Coming To Consoles]. [[Nintendo Life]]. retrieved on April 25, 2018. \"Yes, we're getting a new Castlevania game - but before you get too excited, it's only coming to Apple's iOS...In the meantime,  however, we can't help but feel a little disappointed that Konami isn't focusing on making this a AAA console release; the series certainly deserves that much.\"</ref> However, Konami UK's [[Community management|community manager]], Graham Day, has denied the claims that it was exiting the console industry.<ref>Evangelho, Jason. [https://www.forbes.com/sites/jasonevangelho/2015/09/28/konami-our-commitment-to-aaa-console-games-has-never-changed/#4233e4958b64 Konami: 'Our Commitment To AAA Console Games Has Never Changed']. Retrieved on February 9, 2018</ref>\n\n===Kojima Productions===\n{{Further|Kojima Productions#Closure}}\nOn March 3, 2015, Konami announced they would be shifting focus away from individual studios, notably Kojima Productions. Internal sources claimed the restructure was due to a clash between [[Hideo Kojima]] and Konami.<ref>{{cite web|title=Announcing Official Organizational Restructuring and Personnel Changes|url=http://www.konami-digital-entertainment.co.jp/en/news/release/2015/0303/|website=Konami-digital-entertainment.hk|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ollie|first1=Barder|title=Understanding What Has Really Happened At Konami|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2015/06/02/understanding-what-has-really-happened-at-konami/|website=Forbes.com|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref> References to Kojima were soon stripped from marketing material, and Kojima's position as an executive vice president of Konami Digital Entertainment was removed from the company's official listing of executives.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kain|first1=Erik|title=Konami Cuts Hideo Kojima From 'Metal Gear' Promo Materials|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2015/03/19/konami-cuts-hideo-kojima-from-metal-gear-promo-materials/|website=Forbes|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nLater that year, Konami's legal department barred Kojima from accepting the award for Best Action-Adventure for his work on ''[[Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain]]'' at [[The Game Awards 2015]]. When announced during the event, the audience [[Booing|booed]] in disapproval of Konami's actions. Host [[Geoff Keighley]] expressed his disappointment in Konami's actions. After actor [[Kiefer Sutherland]] accepted the award in Kojima's stead, a choir sang \"Quiet's Theme\" from ''The Phantom Pain'' as a tribute to the absent Kojima.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tach|first1=Dave|title=Konami prevented Kojima from attending the Video Game Awards, host says|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/12/3/9847206/konami-prevented-kojima-attending-video-game-awards-2015|website=Polygon|accessdate=4 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Matulef|first1=Jeffrey|title=Konami blocked Hideo Kojima from attending The Game Awards|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-12-04-konami-blocked-hideo-kojima-from-attending-the-game-awards|website=Euro Gamer|accessdate=4 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Klepek|first1=Patrick|title=Geoff Keighley: Konami Barred Hideo Kojima From Accepting Metal Gear Award|url=http://kotaku.com/geoff-keighley-konami-barred-hideo-kojima-from-accepti-1746111339|website=Kotaku|accessdate=4 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Skipper|first1=Ben|title=The Game Awards: Hideo Kojima banned from attending by Konami as show pays tribute|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/game-awards-hideo-kojima-banned-attending-by-konami-show-pays-tribute-1531785|website=International Business Times|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref> Kojima left Konami several days afterwards, re-opening Kojima Productions as an independent company.\n\n===Treatment of employees and ex-employees===\nIn August 2015, ''[[The Nikkei]]'' criticized Konami for its unethical treatment of employees.<ref>{{cite news | title=\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u3001\u30ab\u30ea\u30b9\u30de\u7d4c\u55b6\u306e\u307b\u3053\u308d\u3073 | url=http://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXMZO89986400R30C15A7000000/ | date=3 August 2015 | newspaper=[[The Nikkei]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Good | first1=Owen S | title=Japanese report says Konami is a deeply unhappy workplace | url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/8/3/9089247/konami-nikkei-report-workplace-culture-metal-gear-solid | website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | accessdate=7 July 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ashcraft|first1=Brian|title=Report: Konami Is Treating Its Staff Like Prisoners|url=https://kotaku.com/report-konami-is-treating-its-staff-like-prisoners-1721700073|website=Kotaku|accessdate=28 February 2018}}</ref> In June 2017, ''The Nikkei'' further reported of Konami's continued clashes with Kojima Productions, preventing the studio's application for health insurance, as well as Konami's actions in making it difficult for former employees to get future jobs; they are notably forbidden to mention their work in Konami on their [[r\u00e9sum\u00e9]]s.<ref>{{cite news | title=\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u3092\u53bb\u308b\u30af\u30ea\u30a8\u30fc\u30bf\u30fc\u305f\u3061\u3000\u738b\u56fd\u306e\u9060\u5fc3\u529b | url=http://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXMZO17452960Y7A600C1000000/ | date=12 June 2017 | newspaper=The Nikkei }}</ref><ref name=\"KonamiExodus\">{{cite web | title=The Konami exodus | url=http://asia.nikkei.com/Business/Companies/The-Konami-exodus | date=14 June 2017 | publisher=Nikkei Asian Review }}</ref> Konami also started filing complaints against other game companies that would hire ex-Konami employees, leading to an unspecified major game company warning its staff against doing so. A former employee of Konami stated: \"If an ex-[Konami employee] is interviewed by the media, the company will send that person a letter through a legal representative, in some cases indicating that Konami is willing to take them to court\"; they also pressured an ex-employee into closing their new business.<ref name=\"KonamiExodus\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tokyo|Companies}}\n* [[Treasure (company)|Treasure]], an independent video game company founded by former Konami employees\n* [[Good-Feel]], another independent video game company founded by former Konami employees\n* [[Ultra Games]]\n* [[List of Konami games]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081216022211/http://www.konami.co.jp/en/ir/ir-data/annualreport.html Konami Annual Report]: [https://web.archive.org/web/20090320094950/http://www.konami.co.jp/en/ir/ir-data/annualreport/report2002/pdf/all-e.pdf 2002], [https://web.archive.org/web/20090320094907/http://www.konami.co.jp/en/ir/ir-data/annualreport/report2003/pdf/all-e.pdf 2003],[https://web.archive.org/web/20090205114923/http://www.konami.co.jp/en/ir/ir-data/annualreport/report2004/pdf/all-e.pdf 2004], [https://web.archive.org/web/20090205114923/http://www.konami.co.jp/en/ir/ir-data/annualreport/report2005/pdf/all-e.pdf 2005], [https://web.archive.org/web/20090205114923/http://www.konami.co.jp/en/ir/ir-data/annualreport/report2006/pdf/all-e.pdf 2006], [https://web.archive.org/web/20090205114923/http://www.konami.co.jp/en/ir/ir-data/annualreport/report2007/pdf/all-e.pdf 2007], [https://web.archive.org/web/20090205122015/http://www.konami.co.jp/en/ir/ir-data/annualreport/report2008/pdf/all.pdf 2008]. Contains summarized history of the company\n* [http://www.konami.co.jp/en/corporate/history/index.html Konami Group History]\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|www.konami.com}}\n\n{{Konami Holdings Corporation}}\n{{Konami franchises}}\n{{Nikkei 225}}\n{{Major video game companies}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Konami| ]]\n[[Category:Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences members]]\n[[Category:Amusement companies of Japan]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the London Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies based in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Entertainment Software Association]]\n[[Category:Health care companies of Japan]]\n[[Category:Holding companies based in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Japanese brands]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1969]]\n[[Category:Slot machine manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Software companies based in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Trading card companies]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 1969]]\n[[Category:Video game companies of Japan]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n[[Category:Video game publishers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Japanese entertainment and gaming company}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Konami Holdings Corporation\n| logo = Konami 4th logo 2.svg\n| image = Headquarters of KONAMI CORPORATION.JPG\n| image_size = 250px\n| image_caption = Konami's former headquarters complex in [[Tokyo Midtown]].\n| native_name = \u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u30db\u30fc\u30eb\u30c7\u30a3\u30f3\u30b0\u30b9\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\n| romanized_name = Konami H\u014drudingusu kabushiki gaisha\n| former_name = Konami Industry Co., Ltd. <small>(1973\u20131991)</small><br />Konami Co., Ltd <small>(1991\u20132000)</small><br />Konami Corporation <small>(2000\u20132015)</small>\n| type = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{Tokyo Stock Exchange|9766}}<br />{{LSE|KNM}}\n| ISIN = JP3300200007\n| industry = {{ubl|[[Video game industry|Video gaming]]|[[Entertainment]]}}\n| founded = {{start date and age|1969|3|21}}\n| founders = [[Kagemasa K\u014dzuki]]\n| location_city = [[Ginza]], [[Ch\u016b\u014d, Tokyo]]\n| location_country = [[Japan]]\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = Kagemasa Kozuki<br />{{small|(Chairman)}}<br />Takuya Kozuki<br />{{small|(President)}}<br>Kimihiko Higashio<br>{{small|(Vice President)}}\n| products = [[List of Konami games]]\n| revenue = {{increase}} [[Japanese yen|\u00a5]] 262.5 billion <small>([[Fiscal year#Japan|2019]])</small><ref name=\"konami.co.jp\">{{cite web|url=https://www.konami.com/ir/en/financialinfo/sales.html|title=Financial Highlights - KONAMI HOLDINGS CORPORATION|website=Konami.com|date=9 May 2019 |accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n| operating_income = {{increase}} [[Japanese yen|\u00a5]] 50.5 billion <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"konami.co.jp\"/>\n| net_income = {{increase}} [[Japanese yen|\u00a5]] 34.2 billion <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"konami.co.jp\"/>\n| num_employees = '''Konami (total)'''<br>10,454 (2019)<ref name=\"auto\"/><br>'''Konami Digital Entertainment'''<br>1,659<ref>https://www.konami.com/games/corporate/en/</ref><br>'''Konami Amusement'''<br>849<ref>https://www.konami.com/amusement/corporate/en/</ref><br>'''Konami Sports'''<br>6,249<ref>https://www.konami.com/sportsclub/corporate/</ref>\n| subsid = {{Unbulleted list\n| Konami Digital Entertainment\n| Konami Amusement\n| Konami Gaming\n| Konami Sports Club\n| Konami Sports Life\n| Konami Business Expert\n| Internet Revolution\n| KME\n| Konami Real Estate\n| [[Konami Cross Media NY]]\n| Kozuki Foundation\n}}\n| owner = Kozuki family (29%)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.konami.com/ir/en/stockbond/stockholderinfo/info/2016_0331.html?cm_sp=00-_-ir-_-stockbond-stockholderinfo-2016-0331-e|title=Shareholders Situation:As of March 31,2016 - KONAMI HOLDINGS CORPORATION|website=Konami.com|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref>\n| homepage = {{URL|www.konami.com}}\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo foot|'''Konami Holdings Corporation'''|\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u30db\u30fc\u30eb\u30c7\u30a3\u30f3\u30b0\u30b9|[[Kabushiki-gaisha]] Konami H\u014drudingusu|post=|group=nb|lead=yes}}<ref group=\"nb\">{{IPAc-en|IPA|k|o\u028a|\u02c8|n|\u0251\u02d0|m|i}} {{respell|koh|NAH|mee}}, {{IPA-ja|ko\ua71cnami|lang}}</ref> is a Japanese entertainment and gambling conglomerate. It operates as a [[product distributor]] (which produces and distributes [[trading card]]s, [[anime]], [[tokusatsu]], [[slot machine]]s, [[Pachinko|pachinko machines]] and [[List of Japanese arcade cabinets|arcade cabinets]]), [[video game developer]] and [[video game publisher|publisher]] company. Konami has casinos around the world and operates health and physical fitness clubs across Japan.\n\nKonami's video game franchisee include ''[[Metal Gear]]'', ''[[Silent Hill]]'', ''[[Castlevania]]'', ''[[Contra (series)|Contra]]'', ''[[Frogger]]'', ''[[Gradius]]'', ''[[Yu-Gi-Oh! Trading Card Game|Yu-Gi-Oh!]]'', ''[[Suikoden]]'' and ''[[Pro Evolution Soccer]]''. Additionally, Konami owns [[Bemani]], known for ''[[Dance Dance Revolution]]'' and ''[[Beatmania]]'', as well as the assets of former game developer [[Hudson Soft]], known for ''[[Bomberman]]'', ''[[Adventure Island (video game)|Adventure Island]]'', ''[[Bonk (series)|Bonk]]'', ''[[Bloody Roar]]'' and ''[[Star Soldier]]''. Konami is the twentieth-largest [[List of video game companies|game company]] in the world by revenue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newzoo.com/free/rankings/top-25-companies-by-game-revenues/|year=2015|title=Top 25 gaming companies|website=Newzoo.com|author=|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe company originated in 1969 as a [[jukebox]] rental and repair business in [[Toyonaka, Osaka]], [[Japan]], by [[Kagemasa K\u014dzuki]], who remains the company's chairman. The name ''Konami'' is a portmanteau of the names Kagemasa '''Ko'''zuki, Yoshinobu '''Na'''kama, and Tatsuo '''Mi'''yasako.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hongkiat.com/blog/popular-gaming-companies-names/|year=2013|title=The Stories Behind the Names of 15 Gaming Brands You Know|website=Hongkiat.com|author=Kelvon Yeezy|accessdate=21 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nKonami is headquartered in [[Tokyo]]. In the United States, Konami manages its video game business from offices in [[El Segundo, California]] and its casino gaming business from offices in [[Paradise, Nevada]]. Its Australian gaming operations are located in [[Sydney]]. As of March 2019, it owns 22 consolidated subsidiaries around the world.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.konami.com/corporate/en/data/|title=Corporate Data - KONAMI HOLDINGS CORPORATION|website=Konami.com|date=31 March 2019|accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:MCM London 2014 - Yu-Gi-Oh! (14269394494).jpg|thumb|The [[Yu-Gi-Oh! Trading Card Game]] is developed and published by Konami. In 2011, [[Guinness World Records]] called it the top-selling trading card game in history, with {{formatnum:25.2 billion}} cards sold worldwide.<ref name=\"Guinness\">{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-7000/best-selling-trading-card-game/|title=Best-selling trading card game company - cumulative|publisher=[[Guinness World Records]]|date=March 31, 2011|accessdate=March 5, 2014}}</ref>]]\n\nThe company was founded on March 21, 1969, and was officially incorporated under the name {{nihongo4|Konami Industry Co., Ltd.|\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u5de5\u696d\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e|Konami K\u014dgy\u014d Kabushiki Gaisha}} on March 19, 1973.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.konami.com/corporate/en/data/|title=Corporate Data - KONAMI HOLDINGS CORPORATION|last=KONAMI|website=Konami.com|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=IGN-history>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/companies/konami|title=Konami History|publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=6 August 2015}}</ref> The company's founder and chairman, Kagemasa Kozuki, ran a jukebox rental and repair business in [[Toyonaka, Osaka]] before transforming the business into a manufacturer of amusement machines for video arcades. Their first coin-operated video game was released in 1978, and they began exporting products to the United States the following year.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web|url=https://www.konami.com/corporate/en/history/|title=Corporate History - KONAMI HOLDINGS CORPORATION|last=KONAMI|date=|website=www.konami.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arcade-museum.com/manuf_detail.php?manuf_id=1467&orig_game_id=&sort=3|title=Konami - coin-operated machines|author=|date=|website=www.arcade-museum.com}}</ref>\n\nKonami began to achieve success with hit arcade games such as 1981's ''[[Frogger]]'', ''[[Scramble (video game)|Scramble]]'', and ''[[Super Cobra]]'', many of which were licensed to other companies for stateside release, including [[Stern (game company)|Stern Electronics]] and [[Gremlin Industries]].  They eventually established their U.S. subsidiary, Konami of America, Inc. in 1982. It was during this period that Konami began expanding their video game business into the home consumer market following a brief stint releasing video games for the [[Atari 2600]] in 1982 for the U.S. market.<ref name=konami_2600>{{cite web|url=http://www.video-game-ephemera.com/012.htm|title=Article 12\u2014KONAMI CES BROCHURE (1983) |website=VIDEO-GAME-EPHEMERA.com}}</ref> The company would release numerous games for the [[MSX]] home computer standard in 1983, followed by the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] in 1985.<ref name=konami_msx_catalog_1>{{cite web|title=MSX software catalog (1983\u20131986)|website=Konami Group Homepage|language=Japanese|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/cs/msx.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19961108212537/http://www.konami.co.jp/cs/msx.html|archive-date=1996-11-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=MSX software catalog (1987\u20131990)|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/cs/msx2.html|website=Konami Group Homepage|language=Japanese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19961108212544/http://www.konami.co.jp/cs/msx2.html|archive-date=1996-11-08}}</ref> Numerous Konami franchises were established during this period on both platforms, as well as the arcades, such as ''[[Gradius]]'', ''[[Castlevania]]'', ''[[Twin Bee]]'', ''[[Ganbare Goemon]]'', ''[[Contra (video game series)|Contra]]'' and ''[[Metal Gear]]''. Due to the success of their NES games, Konami's earnings grew from $10 million in 1987 to $300 million in 1991.<ref>{{cite journal|last= |first= |title=75 Power Players|journal=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=11|publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=November 1995|page=69}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1991, Konami's legal name was changed to {{nihongo4|Konami Co., Ltd.|\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e|Konami Kabushiki Gaisha}} and their headquarters would later be relocated to [[Minato, Tokyo]] in April 1993.<ref name=\"History\"/> The company started supporting the 16-bit video game consoles during this period, starting with the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]] in 1990, followed by the [[TurboGrafx-16|PC Engine]] in 1991 and the [[Sega Genesis]] in 1992.\n\nAfter the launch of the [[Sega Saturn]] and [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] in 1994, Konami became a business divisional organization with the formation of various Konami Computer Entertainment (KCE) subsidiaries, starting with KCE Tokyo and KCE Osaka (which would be later known as KCE Studios) in April 1995, followed by KCE Japan (later known as [[Kojima Productions]]) in April 1996. Each KCE subsidiary would end up creating different [[intellectual properties]] such as KCE Tokyo's ''[[Silent Hill]]'' series and KCE Japan's ''[[Metal Gear Solid]]'' series (a revival of the ''[[Metal Gear]]'' series on [[MSX]]). In 1997, Konami started producing [[rhythm game]]s for arcades under the [[Bemani]] brand and branched off into the [[collectible card game]] business with the launch of the [[Yu-Gi-Oh! Trading Card Game]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/9/28/17910944/dance-dance-revolution-anniversary|title=Dance Dance Revolution made watching games fun before Twitch|author=|date=|website=polygon.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thegamer.com/yu-gi-oh-cards-rare/|title=The 25 Rarest Yu-Gi-Oh Cards (And What They're Worth)|author=|date=18 August 2018|website=thegamer.com}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2000, the company's legal English name was changed to Konami Corporation, but the Japanese legal name remained the same. As the company transitioned into the developing video games for the sixth-generation consoles, they branched out into the health and fitness business with the acquisitions of People Co., Ltd and Daiei Olympic Sports Club, Inc., which became  Konami subsidiaries. In August 2001, Konami invested in another video game developer, [[Hudson Soft]], which became a consolidated subsidiary after Konami accepted new third-party shares issued by them. In March 2006, Konami merged all their video game development divisions into a new subsidiary known as Konami Digital Entertainment Co. (KDE), as the parent company became a pure holding company. Their headquarters were relocated to Minato, Tokyo, in 2007.<ref name=\"History\"/>\n\nThe absorption of [[Hudson Soft]] in 2012 resulted in the addition of several other franchises including: ''[[Adventure Island (video game)|Adventure Island]]'', ''[[Bonk (series)|Bonk]]'', ''[[Bloody Roar]]'', ''[[Bomberman]]'', ''[[Far East of Eden]]'' and ''[[Star Soldier]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/04/nintendo-should-buy-these-5-hudson-soft-games-from.html|title=5 Hudson Soft Games Nintendo Should Buy From Konami|author=|date=|website=pastemagazine.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.konami.com/games/jp/ja/products/search/?page=1&cat=gs&platform=Wii|title=\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u4e00\u89a7 - \u5bb6\u5ead\u7528\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0 - Wii - KONAMI \u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u88fd\u54c1\u30fb\u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9\u60c5\u5831\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8|author=|date=|website=KONAMI \u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u88fd\u54c1\u30fb\u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9\u60c5\u5831\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Konami delisted itself from the New York Stock Exchange following the dissolution of their Kojima Productions subsidiary.<ref name=\"delisting\">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/4/27/8503893/konami-delists-itself-from-new-york-stock-exchange|title=Konami delists itself from New York Stock Exchange|author=Brian Crecente|work=Polygon}}</ref>  In a translated interview with Nikkei Trendy Net published in the following month, the newly appointed CEO of Konami Digital Entertainment, Hideki Hayakawa, announced that Konami would shift their focus towards mobile gaming for a while, claiming that \"mobile is where the future of gaming lies.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/5/14/8605313/konami-interview-mobile-is-where-the-future-of-gaming-lies|title=Konami CEO: 'Mobile is where the future of gaming lies'|last=Crecente|first=Brian|date=2015-05-14|website=Polygon|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-07}}</ref> The trade name of the company was changed from Konami Corporation to Konami Holdings Corporation during the same month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/en/corporate/history/|title=Corporate History|publisher=Konami|accessdate=2015-11-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Konami announced that they would be reviving some of the company's other well-known video game titles following the success of their [[Nintendo Switch]] launch title ''[[Super Bomberman R]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Zarra|first1=Jonathan|title=Super Bomberman R Sales Indicate That It's The Best Selling In Its Franchise In Nearly 20 Years|url=http://nintendork.org/nintendo/super-bomberman-r-sales-indicate-that-its-the-best-selling-in-its-franchise-in-nearly-20-years/|website=Nintendork|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2020, Konami moved their headquarters to the [[Ginza]] district of Tokyo, which includes a facility for holding [[esports]] events as well as a school for esports players.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Batchelor |first1=James |title=Mobile, PES and esports: The three pillars of Konami |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-09-02-mobile-pes-and-esports-the-three-pillars-of-konami |website=GamesIndustry.biz |accessdate=19 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Corporate structure==\n\n===Japan===\n[[File: Konami booth, Taipei Game Show 20170123a.jpg|thumb|Konami Digital Entertainment booth at Taipei Game Show 2017]]\n[[File:KONAMI SPORTS CLUB Toyohashi.jpg|thumb|Konami Sports Club in [[Toyohashi]]. Konami Sports & Life operates fitness clubs across Japan.]]\n* Konami Holdings Corporation\n* Konami Digital Entertainment Co., Ltd.\n* Konami Sports & Life Co., Ltd.\n* Konami Amusement Co., Ltd.\n* Konami Real Estate, Inc.\n* KPE, Inc.\n* Konami Manufacturing and Service, Inc.\n* Konami Facility Service, Inc.\n* KME Co., Ltd.\n* Takasago Electric Industry Co., Ltd.\n* [[Hudson Soft|Hudson Soft Company, Limited]]: On January 20, 2011, Konami Corporation announced turning Hudson Soft Co., Ltd. as its wholly subsidiary via share exchange. The exchange became effective on April 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/1101/release2_english.pdf|title=KONAMI CORPORATION Announces that It will Make a Subsidiary (HUDSON SOFT CO., LTD.) Its Wholly Owned Subsidiary through Share Exchange|access-date=5 November 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6E80cTXte?url=http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/1101/release2_english.pdf|archive-date=2 February 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Digital Golf, Inc.: On January 20, 2011, Konami Corporation announced the acquisition of Digital Golf via share exchange. Digital Golf would become a wholly owned subsidiary of Konami. The exchange became effective on March 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/1101/release_english.pdf|title=KONAMI CORPORATION Announces that It will Make DIGITAL GOLF Inc. Its Wholly Owned Subsidiary through Share Exchange|access-date=5 November 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6E80d4fpT?url=http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/1101/release_english.pdf|archive-date=2 February 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Internet Revolution, Inc.\n* Biz Share Corporation\n* Combi Wellness Corporation\n* The Club At Yebisu Garden Co., Ltd.\n* Konami Holdings Corporation<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/2015/0508/ja_8r5gxy.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-09-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150818102853/http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/2015/0508/ja_8r5gxy.pdf |archivedate=2015-08-18 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inside-games.jp/article/2015/05/09/87448.html|title=\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u300110\u67081\u65e5\u4ed8\u3051\u3067\u300c\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u30db\u30fc\u30eb\u30c7\u30a3\u30f3\u30b0\u30b9\u300d\u306b\u5546\u53f7\u3092\u5909\u66f4 - \u30a4\u30f3\u30b5\u30a4\u30c9|website=Konami.co.jp|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Australia===\n* Konami Australia Pty Ltd (established in 1996)\n\n===America===\n[[File:Konami America booth, E3 20060511.jpg|thumb|Konami America booth at [[E3 2006]]]]\n\n* Konami Corporation of America: Current U.S.-based [[holding company]].\n* Konami Digital Entertainment, Inc.: former American holding company, formerly Konami of America Inc., Konami Corporation of America. On October 13, 2003, Konami Corporation of [[Redwood City, California]] announced it was expanding its operations to El Segundo, California, under the new name of Konami Digital Entertainment, Inc. The Redwood City operations have since been consolidated to El Segundo in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.com/gs/press/konami101303.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060929075753/http://www.konami.com/gs/press/konami101303.html|archivedate=2006-09-29|title=KONAMI ESTABLISHES NEW COMPUTER & VIDEO GAMES OPERATION BASED IN LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA}}</ref>\n** Konami Gaming, Inc. in [[Paradise, Nevada]].\n**[[Konami Cross Media NY]]\n\n===Europe===\n* Konami Digital Entertainment B.V.: European-based holding company.\n* Konami Digital Entertainment GmbH: former holding company Europe, formerly Konami Limited, Konami Corporation of Europe B.V. On March 31, 2003, Konami of Europe announced it would be renamed as Konami Digital Entertainment GmbH at the start of Konami's new financial year, on April 1, 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami-digital-entertainment.de/news.do;jsessionid=335BA44513A82C9A7A42105616EF98EC?idNews=6|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080529143817/http://www.konami-digital-entertainment.de/news.do?idNews=6|archivedate=2008-05-29|title=Introducing Konami Digital Entertainment GmbH}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\n* Konami Digital Entertainment Limited (\u79d1\u6a02\u7f8e\u6578\u78bc\u5a1b\u6a02\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8): Established in September 1994 as Konami (Hong Kong) Limited. Korea and Singapore divisions were established in October 2000. In June 2001, the company changed name to Konami Marketing (Asia) Ltd. (\u79d1\u6a02\u7f8e\u884c\u92b7(\u4e9e\u6d32)\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8). In March 2006, the company was renamed Konami Digital Entertainment Limited.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami-digital-entertainment.hk/aboutus.php?lang=en|title=About Us (English)|website=Konami-digital-entertainment.hk|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami-digital-entertainment.hk/aboutus.php?lang=cn-t|title=About Us (Chinese)|website=Konami-digital-entertainment.hk|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref>\n* Konami Software Shanghai, Inc. (\u79d1\u4e50\u7f8e\u8f6f\u4ef6\uff08\u4e0a\u6d77\uff09\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8): Established in June 2000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.konamish.com.cn/aboutus.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-11-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027224243/http://www.konamish.com.cn/aboutus.html |archivedate=2011-10-27 }}</ref>\n* Konami Digital Entertainment Co. (\uc8fc\uc2dd\ud68c\uc0ac \ucf54\ub098\ubbf8 \ub514\uc9c0\ud138 \uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8): [[South Korea]]-based game producer and distributor, originally established as the Korea branch of Konami Digital Entertainment Limited. On May 1, 2008, it became a separate company, and inherited the existing operations of the former Korea branch in June 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami-korea.kr/company_intro.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080628165903/http://www.konami-korea.kr/company_intro.html|archivedate=2008-06-28|title=KONAMI DIGITAL ENTERTAINMENT \ud68c\uc0ac \uc18c\uac1c}}</ref>\n\nOn November 7, 2005, Konami Corporation announced restructuring Konami Corporation into a holding company, by moving its Japanese Digital Entertainment Business segment under Konami Corporation. The Digital Entertainment Business would become Konami Digital Entertainment Co., Ltd. The newly established Konami Corporation was expected to begin operation on March 31, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2005/11/041/r.17.11.07-e.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110104061140/http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2005/11/041/r.17.11.07-e.html|archivedate=2011-01-04|title=Announcement of Group Restructuring (Merger Between Subsidiaries, Stock Exchange with subsidiary) and Shift to Holding Company Structure by Company Separation}}</ref>\n\n===Konami Digital Entertainment===\n[[File:PASELI Charger.JPG|thumb|[[Paseli]] Charger. Paseli (\u30d1\u30bb\u30ea) is an Electronic Money launched in 2010 by Konami Amusement.]]\n{{nihongo|Konami Digital Entertainment Co., Ltd.|\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u30c7\u30b8\u30bf\u30eb\u30a8\u30f3\u30bf\u30c6\u30a4\u30f3\u30e1\u30f3\u30c8|Kabushiki-gaisha Konami Dejitaru Entateinmento}} is Konami's Japanese video game development and publishing division founded on March 31, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.konami.com/games/corporate/ja/|title=\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u30c7\u30b8\u30bf\u30eb\u30a8\u30f3\u30bf\u30c6\u30a4\u30f3\u30e1\u30f3\u30c8 - \u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u30c7\u30b8\u30bf\u30eb\u30a8\u30f3\u30bf\u30c6\u30a4\u30f3\u30e1\u30f3\u30c8|website=Konami.com|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> Before Konami Corporation had formally changed to a holding company in 2006, various forms of Konami Digital Entertainment companies had been established either as holding company or publisher. The last of the company, the Japan-based Konami Digital Entertainment Co., Ltd., was split from Konami Corporation during the holding company restructuring process.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\n====Subsidiaries====\n*Konami Digital Entertainment Co., Ltd.: Japanese division, established on March 31, 2003.\n*Konami Digital Entertainment, Inc.: North American division, established on October 13, 2003.\n*Konami Digital Entertainment GmbH: European division, established on April 1, 2003.\n*Konami Digital Entertainment Limited: Hong Kong division. Established in September 1994 as Konami (Hong Kong) Limited. In March 2006, it was renamed to Konami Digital Entertainment Limited.\n*KME Co., Ltd (KME Corporation): music division established on October 1, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami-digital-entertainment.co.jp/kme/|title=KME\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e|date=29 May 2011|accessdate=9 November 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110529093217/http://www.konami-digital-entertainment.co.jp/kme/|archivedate=29 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Former subsidiaries===\nKonami Computer Entertainment Nagoya, Inc. (KCEN), founded on October 1, 1996,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/kcen/index.html |title=Company Info |work=\uff2b\uff23\uff25\u540d\u53e4\u5c4b\u30db\u30fc\u30e0\u30da\u30fc\u30b8 |publisher=Konami Co., Ltd. |accessdate=21 August 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021203213358/http://www.konami.co.jp/kcen/index.html |archivedate=3 December 2002}}</ref> was dissolved along with Konami Computer Entertainment Kobe, Inc. (KCEK) in December 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/0212/e/english.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110104174218/http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/0212/e/english.pdf|archivedate=2011-01-04 |title=Consolidated Financial Results for the Third Quarter and the Nine Months Ended December 31, 2002 |date=13 February 2003 |work=Investor Relations |publisher=Konami Co., Ltd. |accessdate=21 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2004, Konami Corporation announced Konami Online, Inc., Konami Computer Entertainment Studios, Inc., Konami Computer Entertainment Tokyo, Inc., Konami Computer Entertainment Japan, Inc. would merge into Konami Corporation, effective on March 1, 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2004/12/045/r.16.12.16-e.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110104083553/http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2004/12/045/r.16.12.16-e.html|archivedate=2011-01-04|title=Konami's Merger with Konami Online}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2004/12/044/r.16.12.16-e.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110104081854/http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2004/12/044/r.16.12.16-e.html|archivedate=2011-01-04|title=Konami's Merger with its Subsidiaries}}</ref>\n\nOn February 22, 2005, Konami Corporation announced Konami Media Entertainment, Inc. would merge into Konami Corporation, effective on March 1, 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2005/02/002/r.17.02.22-e.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110104053544/http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2005/02/002/r.17.02.22-e.html|archivedate=2011-01-04|title=Konami \u2013 KME Merger Announcement}}</ref>\nOn March 11, 2005, Konami Corporation announced Konami Traumer, Inc would be merged back into Konami Corporation, effective on June 1, 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2005/04/013/r.17.04.11-e.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110104045920/http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2005/04/013/r.17.04.11-e.html|archivedate=2011-01-04|title=Announcement: Merger of Konami and Konami Traumer}}</ref>\n\nOn January 5, 2006, Konami Corporation announced the merger of Konami Sports Corporation merged with its parent company, Konami Sports Life Corporation. The parent would be dissolved under the merger, and Konami Sports would become the wholly owned subsidiary of Konami Corporation after share exchange between KC and KS. After the share exchange, KS would be renamed Konami Sports & Life Co., Ltd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2006/01/001/r.18.01.05-e.html|title=Announcement of official agreement for group restructuring (merger between subsidiaries, share exchange with subsidiary) and shift to holding company structure by company separation|website=Konami.co.jp|accessdate=9 November 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090609031519/http://www.konami.co.jp/press/2006/01/001/r.18.01.05-e.html|archivedate=9 June 2009}}</ref> On February 28, 2006, Konami Sports Corporation merged with its parent company, Konami Sports Life Corporation, and became Konami Sports Corporation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konamisportsandlife.com/history/index.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422191741/http://www.konamisportsandlife.com/history/index.html|archivedate=2008-04-22|title=Konami Sports & Life history}}</ref>\n\nOn September 21, 2010, Konami Corporation announced it has signed an agreement to acquire with Abilit Corporation via share exchange. After the transaction, Abilit Corporation became a wholly owned subsidiary of Konami Corporation, effective January 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/9766.T/key-developments/article/1982065|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120910084554/http://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/9766.T/key-developments/article/1982065|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-09-10|title=KONAMI CORPORATION to Acquire Abilit Corporation through Stock Swap | work=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/zaimu/1009/1009_release_english.pdf|title=Execution of Share Exchange Agreement by and between KONAMI CORPORATION and ABILITY CORPORATION|website=Konami.co.jp|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> On January 1, 2011, Abilit Corporation was renamed to Takasago Electric Industry Co.,Ltd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=2445690|title=Abilit Corp.: Private Company Information|website=Investing.businessweek.com|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> As part of the acquisition, Biz Share Corporation also became a subsidiary of Konami Corporation.\n\n====Megacyber Corporation====\nOn October 2, 2006, Konami Corporation announced it had completed the acquisition of mobile phone content developer Megacyber Corporation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/en/news/topics/061002/index.html|title=Announcement of Share Acquisition of Megacyber Corporation|website=Konami.co.jp|accessdate=9 November 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221194718/http://www.konami.co.jp/en/news/topics/061002/index.html|archivedate=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn February 6, 2007, Konami Corporation announced Megacyber Corporation to be merged into Konami Digital Entertainment Co., Ltd., with Konami Digital Entertainment Co., Ltd. being the surviving company, effective on April 1, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/en/news/topics/070206/|title=Announcement of Merger of Konami Digital Entertainment Co., Ltd. and Megacyber Corporation|website=Konami.co.jp|accessdate=9 November 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707180751/http://www.konami.co.jp/en/news/topics/070206/|archivedate=7 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Video games==\n{{main | List of Konami games}}\n[[File:DDR X2.png|thumb|[[Dance Dance Revolution X2]] machine created by Konami.]]\nMajor titles by Konami include the action ''[[Castlevania]]'' series, the survival horror ''[[Silent Hill]]'' series, the action shooter ''[[Contra (video game series)|Contra]]'' series, the platform adventure ''[[Legend of the Mystical Ninja (series)|Ganbare Goemon]]'' series, the stealth action ''[[Metal Gear]]'' series, the role-playing ''[[Suikoden]]'' series, the ''[[List of Bemani series|Bemani]]'' rhythm game series (which includes ''[[Dance Dance Revolution]]'', ''[[Beatmania IIDX]]'', ''[[GuitarFreaks]]'', ''[[DrumMania]]'', and ''[[Pop'n Music]]'', among others), ''[[Dancing with the Stars (video game)|Dancing with the Stars]]'', the dating simulation ''[[Tokimeki Memorial]]'' series, and football simulation ''[[Pro Evolution Soccer]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=A league of their own: six of the best football video games |url=https://www.theguardian.com/games/2018/aug/28/six-best-football-video-games-fifa-pro-evolution-soccer |accessdate=3 November 2018 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nKonami produced its [[shoot 'em up]] arcade games such as ''[[Gradius]]'', ''[[Salamander (video game)|Life Force]]'', ''[[Time Pilot]]'', ''[[Gyruss]]'', ''[[Parodius (series)|Parodius]]'', ''[[Axelay]]'', and ''[[TwinBee]]''. Konami's games based on cartoon licenses, especially the ''[[Batman: The Animated Series]]'', ''[[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles]]'', ''[[Tiny Toon Adventures]]'' and ''[[Animaniacs]]'' series, but other American productions like ''[[The Simpsons]]'', ''[[Bucky O'Hare]]'', ''[[G.I. Joe]]'', ''[[X-Men]]'' and ''[[The Goonies]]'' and French comic ''[[Asterix]]'' all have seen release at some point in the past by Konami either on arcades and/or video game consoles.\n\nSome cinematically styled franchises from Konami are ''[[Silent Hill]]'' [[survival horror]] franchise, and the ''Metal Gear'' series. Another successful franchise is ''[[Pro Evolution Soccer (series)|Winning Eleven]]'', the spiritual sequel to ''[[International Superstar Soccer]]''. In Japan, it is known for the popular ''Jikky\u014d Powerful Pro Yaky\u016b series'' baseball series and the ''[[Zone of the Enders]]'' games. The company has picked up ''[[Saw (video game)|Saw]]'' from [[Brash Entertainment]] when the game's production had been suspended due to financial issues.<ref name=Bloody-Disgusting3>{{cite web|date=2009-02-05|url=http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/12266/|title=Saw videogame picked up by Konami?|accessdate=2009-02-06}}</ref>\n\nKonami is known for its password, the [[Konami Code]], which traditionally gives many [[power-up]]s in its games.\n\n==Film production==\nIn 2006, Konami started producing films based on their franchises. Konami produced the [[Silent Hill (film)|''Silent Hill'' film]] (released in 2006) and announced that they will produce a [[Metal Gear Solid (film)|''Metal Gear Solid'' film]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://videogames.yahoo.com/newsarticle?eid=456314&page=0|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313014619/http://videogames.yahoo.com/newsarticle?eid=456314&page=0|archivedate=2007-03-13|title=Where did the Video Games site go?|publisher=Yahoo}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism and controversy==\n===''Silent Hills'' and reduced video game development===\n{{see also|Silent Hills|P.T. (video game)#Legacy}}\n\n''Silent Hills'', set to be the ninth installment of the ''Silent Hill'' franchise, was abruptly cancelled on April 2015 without explanation despite the critical acclaim and success of ''[[P.T. (video game)|P.T.]]'', a playable teaser.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Dave|title=What it's like to play the best game of 2014, which is about to disappear forever in 2 days|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/silent-hills-pt-review-2015-4|website=Business Insider|accessdate=24 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Orland|first1=Kyle|title=Discontinued PS4 horror demo P.T. worth hundreds on eBay|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2015/05/discontinued-ps4-horror-demo-p-t-worth-hundreds-on-ebay/|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=24 December 2015}}</ref> Hours after the announcement, Konami delisted itself from the New York Stock Exchange.<ref name=\"delisting\" />\n\nGame co-director and writer [[Guillermo del Toro]] publicly criticized the cancellation as not making any sense and questioned what he described as a \"scorched earth\" approach to removing the trailer. Due to the experience, del Toro stated that he would never work on another video game.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Parfitt|first1=Ben|title=Del Toro says killing Silent Hills 'makes no f***ing sense'|url=https://www.mcvuk.com/business/del-toro-says-killing-silent-hills-makes-no-fing-sense|website=MCV|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref><ref>Kuchera, Ben. [https://www.polygon.com/2016/12/2/13817080/guillermo-del-toro-fuck-konami-death-stranding Guillermo del Toro has a simple message: \u2018Fuck Konami\u2019]. [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]. Retrieved on May 10, 2018.</ref>\n\nKonami's CEO, Hideki Hayakawa, announced that \u2013 with few exceptions \u2013 Konami would stop making console games and instead focus on the [[mobile gaming]] platform, a decision that was heavily criticized by the video gaming community.<ref>Crecente, Brian. [https://www.polygon.com/2015/5/14/8605313/konami-interview-mobile-is-where-the-future-of-gaming-lies Konami CEO: 'Mobile is where the future of gaming lies']. [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]. Retrieved on February 11, 2018. Hideki Hayakawa: \"Gaming has spread to many platforms, but at the end of the day, the platform that is always closest to us, is mobile. Mobile is where the future of gaming lies...with multiplatform games, there's no point in dividing the market into categories anymore. Mobiles will take on the new role of linking the general public to the gaming world.\u201d([http://jin115.com/archives/52080348.html Original interview in Japanese])</ref><ref>Usher, William. [https://www.cinemablend.com/games/Konami-Stop-Making-Console-Games-Report-Says-86487.html Konami Will Stop Making Console Games, Report Says]. Cinemablend. Retrieved on January 29, 2018</ref><ref>Knapp, Mark. [https://gamerant.com/konami-gaming-financial-outlook/ Konami Shares Financial Outlook for Gaming]. Gamerant. retrieved on January 29, 2018</ref><ref>McFerran, Damien. [http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/04/konamis_creating_a_new_castlevania_but_its_not_coming_to_consoles Konami's Creating A New Castlevania, But It's Not Coming To Consoles]. [[Nintendo Life]]. retrieved on April 25, 2018. \"Yes, we're getting a new Castlevania game - but before you get too excited, it's only coming to Apple's iOS...In the meantime,  however, we can't help but feel a little disappointed that Konami isn't focusing on making this a AAA console release; the series certainly deserves that much.\"</ref> However, Konami UK's [[Community management|community manager]], Graham Day, has denied the claims that it was exiting the console industry.<ref>Evangelho, Jason. [https://www.forbes.com/sites/jasonevangelho/2015/09/28/konami-our-commitment-to-aaa-console-games-has-never-changed/#4233e4958b64 Konami: 'Our Commitment To AAA Console Games Has Never Changed']. Retrieved on February 9, 2018</ref>\n\n===Kojima Productions===\n{{Further|Kojima Productions#Closure}}\nOn March 3, 2015, Konami announced they would be shifting focus away from individual studios, notably Kojima Productions. Internal sources claimed the restructure was due to a clash between [[Hideo Kojima]] and Konami.<ref>{{cite web|title=Announcing Official Organizational Restructuring and Personnel Changes|url=http://www.konami-digital-entertainment.co.jp/en/news/release/2015/0303/|website=Konami-digital-entertainment.hk|accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ollie|first1=Barder|title=Understanding What Has Really Happened At Konami|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2015/06/02/understanding-what-has-really-happened-at-konami/|website=Forbes.com|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref> References to Kojima were soon stripped from marketing material, and Kojima's position as an executive vice president of Konami Digital Entertainment was removed from the company's official listing of executives.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kain|first1=Erik|title=Konami Cuts Hideo Kojima From 'Metal Gear' Promo Materials|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2015/03/19/konami-cuts-hideo-kojima-from-metal-gear-promo-materials/|website=Forbes|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nLater that year, Konami's legal department barred Kojima from accepting the award for Best Action-Adventure for his work on ''[[Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain]]'' at [[The Game Awards 2015]]. When announced during the event, the audience [[Booing|booed]] in disapproval of Konami's actions. Host [[Geoff Keighley]] expressed his disappointment in Konami's actions. After actor [[Kiefer Sutherland]] accepted the award in Kojima's stead, a choir sang \"Quiet's Theme\" from ''The Phantom Pain'' as a tribute to the absent Kojima.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tach|first1=Dave|title=Konami prevented Kojima from attending the Video Game Awards, host says|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/12/3/9847206/konami-prevented-kojima-attending-video-game-awards-2015|website=Polygon|accessdate=4 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Matulef|first1=Jeffrey|title=Konami blocked Hideo Kojima from attending The Game Awards|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-12-04-konami-blocked-hideo-kojima-from-attending-the-game-awards|website=Euro Gamer|accessdate=4 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Klepek|first1=Patrick|title=Geoff Keighley: Konami Barred Hideo Kojima From Accepting Metal Gear Award|url=http://kotaku.com/geoff-keighley-konami-barred-hideo-kojima-from-accepti-1746111339|website=Kotaku|accessdate=4 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Skipper|first1=Ben|title=The Game Awards: Hideo Kojima banned from attending by Konami as show pays tribute|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/game-awards-hideo-kojima-banned-attending-by-konami-show-pays-tribute-1531785|website=International Business Times|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref> Kojima left Konami several days afterwards, re-opening Kojima Productions as an independent company.\n\n===Treatment of employees and ex-employees===\nIn August 2015, ''[[The Nikkei]]'' criticized Konami for its unethical treatment of employees.<ref>{{cite news | title=\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u3001\u30ab\u30ea\u30b9\u30de\u7d4c\u55b6\u306e\u307b\u3053\u308d\u3073 | url=http://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXMZO89986400R30C15A7000000/ | date=3 August 2015 | newspaper=[[The Nikkei]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Good | first1=Owen S | title=Japanese report says Konami is a deeply unhappy workplace | url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/8/3/9089247/konami-nikkei-report-workplace-culture-metal-gear-solid | website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | accessdate=7 July 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ashcraft|first1=Brian|title=Report: Konami Is Treating Its Staff Like Prisoners|url=https://kotaku.com/report-konami-is-treating-its-staff-like-prisoners-1721700073|website=Kotaku|accessdate=28 February 2018}}</ref> In June 2017, ''The Nikkei'' further reported of Konami's continued clashes with Kojima Productions, preventing the studio's application for health insurance, as well as Konami's actions in making it difficult for former employees to get future jobs; they are notably forbidden to mention their work in Konami on their [[r\u00e9sum\u00e9]]s.<ref>{{cite news | title=\u30b3\u30ca\u30df\u3092\u53bb\u308b\u30af\u30ea\u30a8\u30fc\u30bf\u30fc\u305f\u3061\u3000\u738b\u56fd\u306e\u9060\u5fc3\u529b | url=http://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXMZO17452960Y7A600C1000000/ | date=12 June 2017 | newspaper=The Nikkei }}</ref><ref name=\"KonamiExodus\">{{cite web | title=The Konami exodus | url=http://asia.nikkei.com/Business/Companies/The-Konami-exodus | date=14 June 2017 | publisher=Nikkei Asian Review }}</ref> Konami also started filing complaints against other game companies that would hire ex-Konami employees, leading to an unspecified major game company warning its staff against doing so. A former employee of Konami stated: \"If an ex-[Konami employee] is interviewed by the media, the company will send that person a letter through a legal representative, in some cases indicating that Konami is willing to take them to court\"; they also pressured an ex-employee into closing their new business.<ref name=\"KonamiExodus\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tokyo|Companies}}\n* [[Treasure (company)|Treasure]], an independent video game company founded by former Konami employees\n* [[Good-Feel]], another independent video game company founded by former Konami employees\n* [[Ultra Games]]\n* [[List of Konami games]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081216022211/http://www.konami.co.jp/en/ir/ir-data/annualreport.html Konami Annual Report]: [https://web.archive.org/web/20090320094950/http://www.konami.co.jp/en/ir/ir-data/annualreport/report2002/pdf/all-e.pdf 2002], [https://web.archive.org/web/20090320094907/http://www.konami.co.jp/en/ir/ir-data/annualreport/report2003/pdf/all-e.pdf 2003],[https://web.archive.org/web/20090205114923/http://www.konami.co.jp/en/ir/ir-data/annualreport/report2004/pdf/all-e.pdf 2004], [https://web.archive.org/web/20090205114923/http://www.konami.co.jp/en/ir/ir-data/annualreport/report2005/pdf/all-e.pdf 2005]